A man in his 40s begins to notice a little blood in his stool.

He has no other symptoms but is concerned and decides to see his PCP.

PCP diagnoses him with hemorrhoids and refers him to a GI specialist.

The GI doctor performs a colonoscopy, finds a small mass, and does a biopsy. The results claim the mass is malignant.

The man is told that the mass could be very aggressive and he needs to see an oncologist immediately. The GI doctor sends out a referral to oncology.

The man calls the oncologist to make an appointment and says it's urgent. The oncologist can't see him for almost two months.

The man calls other oncologists who also have the same timeframe for new patient appointments.

He makes an appointment and waits.

His day finally comes to see the oncologist who tells him that his cancer is so aggressive that if he wants to live, he either needs chemo & radiation or surgery.

The GI doctor and the oncologist both claim the cancer is "aggressive" yet it took two months just to get in and be seen to talk about options.

This oncologist is someone he's never met before, someone his own doctor doesn't even know, someone he's supposed to trust with his life, and he's telling this man to poison his body or undergo a surgery that will require him to have a colostomy bag for the rest of his life.

The oncologist uses death as a fear factor to get this man to agree to toxic expensive treatments.

Since the man is young and very active, he wants to avoid surgery, so he chooses treatment.

He undergoes chemotherapy and radiation. His wife drives him back and forth to his treatment appointments twice a week for six months.

It poisons his body, kills his immune system, and he feels sick all the time. He doesn't have the energy to spend time with his family or even work. 

After he's completed all treatments, he goes in to see his oncologist again for a follow-up.

They do another colonoscopy. 

It shows the mass is still there and it's still the same size as it was when he first had a colonoscopy eight months prior.

He's been poisoning his body and spending tens of thousands of dollars just to find out the mass hasn't changed.

What does the oncologist say?

"It may not have changed, but at least the chemo and radiation prevented it from growing."

The man is furious wondering if the mass was even malignant to begin with. But, the oncologist claims that the mass is still there and it's still aggressive.

The man ends up getting surgery to remove the "aggressive mass."

All that time, all those toxic poisons, all that money spent to avoid surgery, and he ended up getting surgery anyway.

My questions would be:

Was there even a mass at all?

If so, and it didn't change, it hadn't even grown from the time he first had the colonoscopy to the two months it took to even see an oncologist and start treatment, was it actually "aggressive" like they said it was?

Since it didn't even change from all that chemo & radiation, was it really malignant or was it benign?

I'm starting to wonder if some of these cancer diagnoses are false positives and these oncologists are full of ðŸ’©
